WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-

2
00:00:27.026 --> 00:00:30.238
<i>They say Japan was made
by a sword.</i>

3
00:00:32.031 --> 00:00:35.785
<i>They say the old gods dipped
a coral blade into the ocean...</i>

4
00:00:35.952 --> 00:00:40.748
<i>...and when they pulled it out.
four perfect drops fell back into the sea...</i>

5
00:00:40.915 --> 00:00:44.377
<i>...and those drops became
the islands of Japan.</i>

6
00:00:46.087 --> 00:00:50.466
<i>I say Japan was made
by a handful of brave men...</i>

7
00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:54.554
<i>...warriors willing to give their lives...</i>

8
00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:57.431
<i>...for what seems to have become
a forgotten word:</i>

9
00:00:58.766 --> 00:01:00.101
<i>Honor.</i>

10
00:01:55.156 --> 00:01:58.868
Ladies and gentlemen:
Winchester.

11
00:01:59.035 --> 00:02:03.331
America's leader in all forms of armament
used by the United States Army...

12
00:02:03.497 --> 00:02:08.419
...celebrates our nation's centennial
by bringing you a true American hero.

13
00:02:09.837 --> 00:02:13.674
One of the most decorated warriors
this country has ever known.

14
00:02:13.841 --> 00:02:16.511
Winner of the Medal of Honor...

15
00:02:16.719 --> 00:02:20.431
...for his gallantry
on the hallowed ground of Gettysburg.

16
00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:23.476
He is late of the 7th Cavalry...

17
00:02:23.643 --> 00:02:27.772
...and their triumphant campaign against
the most savage of the Indian nations.

18
00:02:27.980 --> 00:02:32.276
Ladies and gentlemen.
I present to you:

19
00:02:32.818 --> 00:02:35.571
Captain Nathan Algren!

20
00:02:42.703 --> 00:02:46.958
Captain Nathan Algren!

21
00:02:47.667 --> 00:02:48.960
Yes!

22
00:02:49.168 --> 00:02:50.127
Yes!

23
00:02:52.004 --> 00:02:54.549
One moment.
ladies and gentlemen.

24
00:02:57.301 --> 00:02:59.595
Goddamn you. Algren.
get out there!

25
00:02:59.762 --> 00:03:03.975
This is your last performance!
You're fired! Now get out there!

26
00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:08.104
Come on! I'm sick of this!

27
00:03:08.396 --> 00:03:09.605
Come on!

28
00:03:10.898 --> 00:03:11.899
Yes!

29
00:03:19.782 --> 00:03:23.202
My thanks. Mr. McCabe.
you are too kind.

30
00:03:25.037 --> 00:03:27.874
This. ladies and gents...

31
00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:31.127
...is the gun that's winning the West.

32
00:03:31.294 --> 00:03:34.463
Why. many's the time I've found myself...

33
00:03:36.465 --> 00:03:39.677
...surrounded by a swarm of...

34
00:03:41.804 --> 00:03:43.931
...angry hostiles...

35
00:03:44.098 --> 00:03:46.767
...with nothing but this rifle...

36
00:03:46.934 --> 00:03:51.606
...between me and a certain
and gruesome death.

37
00:03:52.273 --> 00:03:55.026
And let me tell you. folks.
the red man...

38
00:03:55.902 --> 00:03:58.279
...is a fearsome enemy.

39
00:03:58.446 --> 00:04:00.198
And if he'd had his way...

40
00:04:00.406 --> 00:04:03.743
...why. this scalp of mine
would be long gone...

41
00:04:03.910 --> 00:04:07.496
...and there'd be a balder man
standing before you today.

42
00:04:13.085 --> 00:04:15.963
Like those poor bastards out there...

43
00:04:16.672 --> 00:04:18.758
...on the Little Bighorn.

44
00:04:20.801 --> 00:04:23.012
Bodies stripped bare...

45
00:04:24.347 --> 00:04:26.098
...mutilated.

46
00:04:27.558 --> 00:04:29.852
Left to rot in the sun.

47
00:04:33.731 --> 00:04:38.402
This. ladies and gentlemen.
the 73 lever-action...

48
00:04:38.778 --> 00:04:40.404
...Trapper.

49
00:04:40.821 --> 00:04:45.201
It's got a seven-shot capacity.
Accurate 400 yards. one round per second.

50
00:04:45.826 --> 00:04:48.746
Son. have you ever seen
what this could do to a man?

51
00:04:48.913 --> 00:04:51.791
This would blow a hole
in your daddy six inches wide.

52
00:04:51.958 --> 00:04:53.251
That's right. missy.

53
00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:55.336
This beauty.

54
00:04:55.503 --> 00:05:00.007
You could kill yourself five. six. seven
braves without ever having to reload.

55
00:05:00.174 --> 00:05:04.053
Note the patented loading port
and the smooth cocking action.

56
00:05:20.111 --> 00:05:24.031
My thanks on behalf
of those who died...

57
00:05:24.198 --> 00:05:27.827
...in the name of better
mechanical amusements...

58
00:05:28.327 --> 00:05:30.329
...and commercial opportunities.

59
00:05:31.330 --> 00:05:33.958
Mr. McCabe here will take your orders.

60
00:05:34.333 --> 00:05:36.460
God bless you all.

61
00:05:44.177 --> 00:05:47.513
I must say. captain. you have a flair
for the old melodrama.

62
00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.975
- You're alive.
- I am. indeed.

63
00:05:51.559 --> 00:05:55.271
Your man Custer says to me.
"We're going to the Little Bighorn. "

64
00:05:55.438 --> 00:05:58.858
Says I. "What's this 'we' stuff?"
It's the walking ticket for me.

65
00:05:59.025 --> 00:06:01.819
Nine lives I have.
But I'll tell you what else I have.

66
00:06:01.986 --> 00:06:03.988
I have a good job for the both of us.

67
00:06:04.155 --> 00:06:06.824
God knows it looks
as if you'll need one real soon.

68
00:06:06.991 --> 00:06:08.993
What kind of a job?

69
00:06:09.202 --> 00:06:13.998
The only job you're fit for. boyo.
A man's job.

70
00:06:15.291 --> 00:06:19.003
Unless. of course. you got your heart
set on a career in the theater.

71
00:06:23.174 --> 00:06:24.759
Nathan!

72
00:06:24.926 --> 00:06:27.220
Just listen to what
your man has to say.

73
00:06:27.386 --> 00:06:29.388
Been a while.
It's good to see you.

74
00:06:29.972 --> 00:06:32.517
I'd like you to meet
Mr. Omura from Japan...

75
00:06:32.683 --> 00:06:36.687
...and his associate. whose name
I've given up trying to pronounce.

76
00:06:36.854 --> 00:06:37.980
Sit down. please.

77
00:06:43.778 --> 00:06:45.029
Whiskey.

78
00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:50.701
Now. Japan's got it in mind
to become a civilized country.

79
00:06:50.868 --> 00:06:53.746
And Mr. Omura here is willing
to spend what it takes...

80
00:06:53.913 --> 00:06:56.582
...to hire white experts
to train their army.

81
00:06:56.749 --> 00:06:58.751
And if we play our cards right...

82
00:06:58.918 --> 00:07:02.547
...the Emperor grants the U.S.
Exclusive rights to supply arms.

83
00:07:08.928 --> 00:07:12.390
Well. I have an agreement
with Winchester Company.

84
00:07:12.598 --> 00:07:15.893
I'm certain Mr. Omura has some concept
of what an agreement is.

85
00:07:16.102 --> 00:07:21.482
Your performances for the Winchester
Company bring you $25 a week.

86
00:07:21.649 --> 00:07:24.318
We will pay you $400 a month.

87
00:07:29.282 --> 00:07:31.868
Five. For each.

88
00:07:32.577 --> 00:07:36.539
And another 500
when we get the job done.

89
00:07:37.373 --> 00:07:41.586
How many other genuine heroes
you got lined up?

90
00:07:48.968 --> 00:07:49.969
Whiskey.

91
00:07:50.136 --> 00:07:53.014
So who will we be training
your boys to fight?

92
00:07:53.472 --> 00:07:57.768
His name is Katsumoto Moritsugu.
He was once the Emperor's teacher.

93
00:07:58.644 --> 00:08:01.105
- He's Samurai.
- Samurai?

94
00:08:01.272 --> 00:08:03.608
The word you might use is "warrior. "

95
00:08:03.774 --> 00:08:07.361
Mr. Omura is familiar with our experiences
dealing with renegades.

96
00:08:07.528 --> 00:08:09.447
Is he?

97
00:08:09.614 --> 00:08:11.282
He's even read your book.

98
00:08:11.449 --> 00:08:13.576
Captain Algren's study of the tribes...

99
00:08:13.743 --> 00:08:16.662
...was a crucial factor
in our defeat of the Cheyenne.

100
00:08:30.051 --> 00:08:32.595
Please excuse. What is funny?

101
00:08:34.722 --> 00:08:39.352
The corps back together again.
It's just so...

102
00:08:40.019 --> 00:08:42.563
...inspiring!

103
00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:49.237
Excuse me.

104
00:08:52.198 --> 00:08:54.784
I need to use the necessities.

105
00:08:58.246 --> 00:09:01.332
This isn't a problem.
I'll just talk to him for a minute.

106
00:09:01.541 --> 00:09:03.000
Colonel Bagley.

107
00:09:03.209 --> 00:09:06.796
We contacted you because you are
Captain Algren's superior officer...

108
00:09:07.004 --> 00:09:09.423
...and you assured us
of his participation.

109
00:09:09.590 --> 00:09:12.844
He'll do it.
I just need a minute.

110
00:09:15.388 --> 00:09:16.764
Nathan.

111
00:09:18.683 --> 00:09:21.561
I did what I was ordered
to do out there.

112
00:09:22.061 --> 00:09:23.604
And I have no remorse.

113
00:09:25.231 --> 00:09:27.650
So. what do you say we
put the past behind us?

114
00:09:31.445 --> 00:09:35.700
- You want me to kill Jappos. I'll kill them.
- I'm not asking you to kill anybody.

115
00:09:35.908 --> 00:09:39.620
You want me to kill the enemies of Jappos.
I'll kill their enemies.

116
00:09:40.246 --> 00:09:43.499
Rebs or Sioux or Cheyenne...

117
00:09:43.666 --> 00:09:47.170
For 500 bucks a month.
I'll kill whoever you want.

118
00:09:47.712 --> 00:09:49.714
But keep one thing in mind...

119
00:09:51.299 --> 00:09:54.177
...I'd happily kill you for free.

120
00:10:09.859 --> 00:10:12.570
<i>July 12th. 1876.</i>

121
00:10:12.737 --> 00:10:15.323
<i>There is some comfort
in the emptiness of the sea.</i>

122
00:10:16.449 --> 00:10:19.952
<i>No past. no future.</i>

123
00:10:22.038 --> 00:10:26.167
<i>And then at once. I am confronted
by the hard truth of present circumstances.</i>

124
00:10:29.504 --> 00:10:34.509
<i>I have been hired to help suppress
the rebellion of yet another tribal leader.</i>

125
00:10:34.675 --> 00:10:38.429
<i>Apparently. this is the only job
for which I am suited.</i>

126
00:10:40.765 --> 00:10:44.685
<i>I am beset by the ironies of my life.</i>

127
00:11:54.881 --> 00:11:57.258
- Captain Algren. I presume?
- Yes.

128
00:11:57.425 --> 00:11:59.886
Jolly good. How do you do?
Simon Graham.

129
00:12:00.178 --> 00:12:03.556
Twenty years ago.
this was a sleepy little town.

130
00:12:03.723 --> 00:12:05.016
Now look at it.

131
00:12:05.224 --> 00:12:08.436
You see. the Emperor is mad
for all things Western...

132
00:12:08.603 --> 00:12:11.647
...and the Samurai believe
it's changing too fast.

133
00:12:11.814 --> 00:12:14.859
The ancient and the modern
are at war for the soul of Japan.

134
00:12:15.067 --> 00:12:18.029
So your new employer. Mr. Omura.
is bringing in...

135
00:12:18.237 --> 00:12:20.448
...every Western expert he can get.

136
00:12:20.615 --> 00:12:24.535
Lawyers from France. engineers from
Germany. architects from Holland...

137
00:12:24.702 --> 00:12:28.122
...and now. of course.
warriors from America.

138
00:12:28.289 --> 00:12:32.877
I came over with the British
trade mission. oh. years ago.

139
00:12:33.044 --> 00:12:34.879
I was soon relieved of my position.

140
00:12:35.087 --> 00:12:37.673
I had an unfortunate tendency
to tell the truth...

141
00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:40.635
...in a country where no one ever
says what they mean.

142
00:12:40.801 --> 00:12:45.181
So now. I very accurately translate
other people's lies.

143
00:12:50.436 --> 00:12:53.648
For 2000 years. no emperor
was even seen by a commoner.

144
00:12:53.814 --> 00:12:58.402
You have to realize what an honor this is.
It's all highly ritualized. of course.

145
00:12:58.569 --> 00:13:01.447
You may look at him.
but do not speak unless spoken to.

146
00:13:01.614 --> 00:13:05.576
If he stands. you must bow.
If he bows. you must bow lower.

147
00:13:05.785 --> 00:13:08.829
Do I look presentable?
I haven't worn this in a decade.

148
00:13:09.830 --> 00:13:12.166
Rather snug around the midriff.

149
00:13:27.431 --> 00:13:29.183
And bow.

150
00:13:30.476 --> 00:13:33.396
The divine Emperor Meiji
bids you welcome.

151
00:13:33.563 --> 00:13:36.774
He is grateful for the assistance
your country offers.

152
00:13:37.483 --> 00:13:42.655
We hope to accomplish the same national
harmony you enjoy in your homeland.

153
00:13:50.329 --> 00:13:53.416
The Emperor is most interested
in your American Indians...

154
00:13:53.583 --> 00:13:56.002
...if you have fought
against them in battle.

155
00:13:56.169 --> 00:13:59.297
We have. Your Highness.
The red man is a brutal adversary.

156
00:14:07.638 --> 00:14:09.974
The Emperor wishes
to ask Captain Algren...

157
00:14:10.141 --> 00:14:12.810
...if it is true they wear eagle feathers...

158
00:14:13.019 --> 00:14:16.063
...and paint their faces
before going into battle...

159
00:14:16.230 --> 00:14:18.441
...and that they have no fear.

160
00:14:21.527 --> 00:14:23.321
They are very brave.

161
00:14:31.954 --> 00:14:33.456
Bow.

162
00:14:41.380 --> 00:14:45.009
Thank you very much.

163
00:14:55.978 --> 00:14:58.773
And step back.

164
00:14:59.982 --> 00:15:04.403
Step back. step back and turn.

165
00:15:07.448 --> 00:15:09.867
Right. you little bastards!

166
00:15:10.034 --> 00:15:13.704
You will stand up straight
or I will personally shit-kick...

167
00:15:13.871 --> 00:15:17.333
...every Far Eastern buttock
that appears before my eyes!

168
00:15:19.669 --> 00:15:21.254
Well done. sergeant.

169
00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:24.674
When you understand the language.
everything falls into place.

170
00:15:24.924 --> 00:15:27.635
The first rank will kneel.
rifles at the ready.

171
00:15:29.220 --> 00:15:30.179
The second rank...

172
00:15:30.388 --> 00:15:33.391
<i>July 22nd. 1876.</i>

173
00:15:34.225 --> 00:15:38.813
<i>For six months' work. I am to receive
three years of captain's pay...</i>

174
00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:41.607
<i>...teaching Orientals to soldier.</i>

175
00:15:43.734 --> 00:15:45.820
<i>They are an army of conscripts.</i>

176
00:15:45.987 --> 00:15:48.990
<i>Most of them are peasants
who have never even seen a gun.</i>

177
00:15:49.156 --> 00:15:50.783
Fire!

178
00:15:52.201 --> 00:15:55.413
<i>They are led by General Hasegawa.
a man of small stature...</i>

179
00:15:55.621 --> 00:15:58.416
<i>...who nonetheless commands
enormous respect.</i>

180
00:15:58.583 --> 00:16:02.587
What can the general tell me about
this man. this Samurai. Katsumoto?

181
00:16:07.717 --> 00:16:11.179
<i>He seems to have great knowledge
of Katsumoto and his rebellion.</i>

182
00:16:11.345 --> 00:16:13.890
<i>I will count on his help
when facing the Samurai.</i>

183
00:16:14.056 --> 00:16:15.892
Who supplies their weapons?

184
00:16:23.816 --> 00:16:27.528
Katsumoto no longer dishonors himself
by using firearms. you see.

185
00:16:28.237 --> 00:16:29.697
He uses no firearms?

186
00:16:29.864 --> 00:16:32.783
To those who honor the old ways.
Katsumoto is a hero.

187
00:16:33.326 --> 00:16:34.702
How well does he know him?

188
00:16:34.869 --> 00:16:38.122
The general and Katsumoto
fought together for the Emperor.

189
00:16:38.289 --> 00:16:39.707
He fought with the Samurai?

190
00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:43.628
He is Samurai.

191
00:16:50.384 --> 00:16:54.764
You must understand. Katsumoto pledged
his sword to defend the Emperor.

192
00:16:54.931 --> 00:16:57.642
They say that a Samurai's sword
is his soul.

193
00:16:57.808 --> 00:17:02.647
Samurai are paradoxical. I've tried to write
about them. but they keep to themselves.

194
00:17:02.813 --> 00:17:05.316
The bastards are still wearing armor.

195
00:17:05.525 --> 00:17:08.694
When the Irish were comporting
themselves in loincloths...

196
00:17:08.861 --> 00:17:12.073
...these chaps were the most
sophisticated warriors on Earth.

197
00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:14.367
I need information
on their battle tactics.

198
00:17:14.575 --> 00:17:17.662
I have several more books
just waiting to be translated.

199
00:17:17.870 --> 00:17:22.291
He'll be speaking the lingo in no time.
You should hear him blather on in Blackfoot.

200
00:17:22.458 --> 00:17:23.960
Really?

201
00:17:24.126 --> 00:17:26.921
A fellow linguist? Oh. capital!

202
00:17:27.088 --> 00:17:30.341
Come on. sir.
A word or two in the savage tongue.

203
00:17:30.508 --> 00:17:34.011
Just "hello" or "goodbye" or...
No. no. no!

204
00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:36.681
"Cut his tongue out
and boil him in oil. "

205
00:17:39.058 --> 00:17:41.185
Early day tomorrow. captain.

206
00:17:41.394 --> 00:17:45.231
- It's about bedtime. isn't it?
- I always had a fascination with scalping.

207
00:17:45.398 --> 00:17:48.234
I never quite understood
its technique.

208
00:17:53.364 --> 00:17:57.785
Imagine someone who hates you
with the utmost intensity...

209
00:17:58.077 --> 00:18:02.957
...grabbing a handful of your hair
while you're lying prostrate and helpless...

210
00:18:08.713 --> 00:18:12.341
...and scraping a dull blade
of a rusty knife around your scalp...

211
00:18:12.508 --> 00:18:14.802
...with a saw-like motion.

212
00:18:15.595 --> 00:18:20.558
And let your imagination grasp. if you can.
the effect of a strong. quick jerk...

213
00:18:21.934 --> 00:18:25.229
...on the turf of your hair
to release any clinging particles...

214
00:18:25.438 --> 00:18:28.191
...would have on your nervous system.

215
00:18:32.236 --> 00:18:36.073
And you'll have some idea
of how it feels to be scalped...

216
00:18:36.282 --> 00:18:37.408
...Mr. Graham.

217
00:18:44.332 --> 00:18:46.417
How soon can you
translate those books?

218
00:18:48.794 --> 00:18:50.588
Right away.

219
00:18:52.590 --> 00:18:56.219
I'm just delighted you're taking
such an interest in Samurai.

220
00:18:56.385 --> 00:18:59.805
I don't give a damn about the Samurai.
I want to know my enemy.

221
00:18:59.972 --> 00:19:03.392
I shall not sleep until it is done.

222
00:19:05.895 --> 00:19:07.396
Sake.

223
00:19:08.314 --> 00:19:10.149
I bid you good night.

224
00:19:11.275 --> 00:19:12.443
Can I get you anything?

225
00:19:12.652 --> 00:19:14.695
<i>This is a punitive expedition. captain.</i>

226
00:19:14.862 --> 00:19:18.032
Col. Bagley. these people had
nothing to do with the raids!

227
00:19:18.199 --> 00:19:20.785
- Good night. sir.
- Quietly now. boys.

228
00:20:06.539 --> 00:20:07.790
Fire!

229
00:20:17.341 --> 00:20:20.636
We should be grateful they're all firing
in the same direction.

230
00:20:20.803 --> 00:20:23.055
Couldn't have put it better myself. sir.

231
00:20:26.851 --> 00:20:29.812
Rifle butt. against the shoulder.

232
00:20:31.564 --> 00:20:34.025
Eye. down the sight.

233
00:20:34.358 --> 00:20:35.860
Now. slowly...

234
00:20:40.907 --> 00:20:42.408
Well done.

235
00:20:43.701 --> 00:20:45.286
Nathan!

236
00:20:49.207 --> 00:20:52.418
Katsumoto's attacked a railroad
at the border of his province.

237
00:20:52.585 --> 00:20:55.796
We cannot govern a country
in which we cannot travel freely.

238
00:20:55.963 --> 00:20:57.215
He must be stopped now.

239
00:20:57.381 --> 00:21:00.968
My railroad is a priority
for this country.

240
00:21:01.469 --> 00:21:02.470
They're not ready.

241
00:21:02.637 --> 00:21:06.432
The rebels don't have any rifles.
They're savages with bows and arrows.

242
00:21:06.641 --> 00:21:10.228
Whose sole occupation for the last
thousand years has been war.

243
00:21:10.436 --> 00:21:14.190
You have superior firepower
and a larger force.

244
00:21:14.941 --> 00:21:17.902
I am ordering the regiment
to move against Katsumoto.

245
00:21:18.069 --> 00:21:21.405
You will track him down
and engage him.

246
00:21:25.076 --> 00:21:26.244
Load.

247
00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:29.747
Mr. Graham!
Tell this man to fire at me!

248
00:21:29.956 --> 00:21:33.417
- I beg your pardon?
- Tell this man...

249
00:21:33.626 --> 00:21:37.171
...if he does not shoot me.
I will kill him!

250
00:21:38.172 --> 00:21:41.425
- Captain. if I might have a word.
- Tell him!

251
00:21:43.010 --> 00:21:44.595
Tell him!

252
00:21:50.685 --> 00:21:52.270
Load!

253
00:21:56.232 --> 00:21:57.984
Load!

254
00:22:01.112 --> 00:22:02.238
Faster!

255
00:22:03.614 --> 00:22:04.782
Faster!

256
00:22:09.662 --> 00:22:11.789
Shoot me. damn it.

257
00:22:16.252 --> 00:22:17.962
Fire!

258
00:22:20.047 --> 00:22:21.257
Fire!

259
00:22:47.867 --> 00:22:49.118
They're not ready.

260
00:22:52.038 --> 00:22:54.582
The regiment leaves at 6 a. m.!

261
00:23:25.613 --> 00:23:29.534
A thousand miles of rail track laid
in less than two years.

262
00:23:29.700 --> 00:23:31.369
It's astonishing.

263
00:23:31.536 --> 00:23:33.621
And Omura owns all of it?

264
00:23:33.788 --> 00:23:36.791
As soon as he can get rid
of the Samurai. he will. yes.

265
00:23:36.958 --> 00:23:39.502
How do you intend
to find Katsumoto?

266
00:23:39.669 --> 00:23:44.215
Don't worry. Mr. Graham.
I assure you. he'll find us.

267
00:23:55.226 --> 00:23:57.687
Move into position!

268
00:23:57.854 --> 00:24:00.523
1st Company.
form a battle line on me!

269
00:24:00.690 --> 00:24:02.650
Pay attention.
it will save your life!

270
00:24:02.817 --> 00:24:05.444
2nd Company.
form on 1st Company.

271
00:24:05.611 --> 00:24:07.947
3rd and 4th Company.
form up behind.

272
00:24:08.114 --> 00:24:09.657
Fill in on command!

273
00:24:09.824 --> 00:24:13.661
- Where's Hasegawa?
- He refuses to fight against Katsumoto.

274
00:24:16.706 --> 00:24:19.166
- Cover down!
- Captain Algren.

275
00:24:19.876 --> 00:24:21.294
We are not here as combatants.

276
00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:24.088
- Then who's gonna lead them?
- Their own officers.

277
00:24:24.255 --> 00:24:27.049
- Let's move to the rear.
- We'll be there presently.

278
00:24:27.341 --> 00:24:28.759
Fix bayonets!

279
00:24:33.014 --> 00:24:37.393
- Mr. Graham. accompany me to the rear.
- Yes. of course.

280
00:24:41.981 --> 00:24:47.111
Sergeant Gant. report to the rear and see
to the disposition of the supply trains.

281
00:24:47.570 --> 00:24:50.114
- Did you hear my order?
- I did indeed. sir!

282
00:24:50.323 --> 00:24:52.617
Then you will obey it. Now!

283
00:24:52.825 --> 00:24:56.204
No disrespect intended. sir.
but shove it up your ass.

284
00:25:01.584 --> 00:25:03.461
- Load!
- Load!

285
00:25:32.073 --> 00:25:33.241
Samurai come.

286
00:25:35.326 --> 00:25:36.494
You'll be fine. son.

287
00:25:54.637 --> 00:25:57.098
- Assume firing positions!
- Assume firing positions!

288
00:26:10.695 --> 00:26:13.114
Fire on my order only!

289
00:26:34.886 --> 00:26:36.220
Hold your fire!

290
00:26:36.846 --> 00:26:38.055
Hold your fire!

291
00:26:45.396 --> 00:26:47.023
Reload!

292
00:26:51.402 --> 00:26:53.070
Hold the line!

293
00:26:54.780 --> 00:26:56.574
Fire at will!

294
00:27:12.715 --> 00:27:14.091
Lieutenant. fall back!

295
00:27:57.510 --> 00:27:58.928
Zeb!

296
00:32:26.070 --> 00:32:27.405
What is your name?

297
00:32:55.391 --> 00:32:57.185
This is my son's village.

298
00:32:57.351 --> 00:33:01.063
We are deep in the mountains
and winter is coming. You cannot escape.

299
00:33:04.192 --> 00:33:05.943
Jolly good.

300
00:35:57.532 --> 00:35:58.783
Sake.

301
00:36:00.451 --> 00:36:01.994
Sake?

302
00:36:02.245 --> 00:36:04.455
Sake.

303
00:36:11.838 --> 00:36:13.130
Sake.

304
00:36:15.383 --> 00:36:16.926
Sake.

305
00:37:16.903 --> 00:37:18.487
Sake.

306
00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:22.283
Sake!

307
00:37:35.546 --> 00:37:36.964
Please.

308
00:37:37.381 --> 00:37:38.841
Sake.

309
00:37:48.518 --> 00:37:50.978
Sake!

310
00:37:57.443 --> 00:38:00.279
No!

311
00:38:01.447 --> 00:38:03.533
No!

312
00:38:07.495 --> 00:38:10.414
I told you!

313
00:38:17.338 --> 00:38:19.715
No!

314
00:39:03.426 --> 00:39:04.802
Morning.

315
00:40:57.999 --> 00:41:00.710
Go. You. go.

316
00:41:02.128 --> 00:41:03.754
What's your name?

317
00:41:04.338 --> 00:41:06.257
You got a name. don't you?

318
00:41:10.261 --> 00:41:12.638
You don't know what I'm saying. do you?

319
00:41:14.015 --> 00:41:15.516
I know why you don't talk.

320
00:41:16.851 --> 00:41:18.519
You're angry.

321
00:41:18.686 --> 00:41:21.731
You're angry because
they make you wear a dress.

322
00:41:23.316 --> 00:41:24.567
Son of a bitch.

323
00:42:03.856 --> 00:42:07.485
This temple was built by my family
a thousand years ago.

324
00:42:09.904 --> 00:42:12.490
My name is Katsumoto.

325
00:42:12.698 --> 00:42:15.493
What is your name?

326
00:42:21.499 --> 00:42:24.335
Are my words not correct?

327
00:42:28.881 --> 00:42:31.759
I will practice my English with you...

328
00:42:33.219 --> 00:42:35.096
...if you would honor me.

329
00:42:36.889 --> 00:42:39.016
You kept me alive just to speak English?

330
00:42:41.227 --> 00:42:43.020
Then what do you want?

331
00:42:44.355 --> 00:42:45.648
To know my enemy.

332
00:42:47.191 --> 00:42:49.861
I've seen what you do to your enemies.

333
00:42:50.236 --> 00:42:52.196
Warriors in your country do not kill?

334
00:42:52.405 --> 00:42:55.658
They don't cut the heads off defeated.
kneeling men.

335
00:42:56.701 --> 00:43:00.371
General Hasegawa asked me
to help him end his life.

336
00:43:01.914 --> 00:43:05.293
A Samurai cannot stand
the shame of defeat.

337
00:43:06.043 --> 00:43:08.212
I was honored to cut off his head.

338
00:43:11.299 --> 00:43:16.137
Many of our customs seem strange to you.
The same is true of yours.

339
00:43:16.304 --> 00:43:17.847
For example...

340
00:43:18.014 --> 00:43:22.977
...not to introduce yourself is considered
extremely rude. even among enemies.

341
00:43:29.775 --> 00:43:31.569
Nathan Algren.

342
00:43:34.113 --> 00:43:36.490
I am honored to meet you.

343
00:43:37.116 --> 00:43:41.037
- I have enjoyed this conversation in English.
- I have questions.

344
00:43:41.204 --> 00:43:44.874
I have introduced myself.
You have introduced yourself.

345
00:43:45.041 --> 00:43:47.168
This is a very good conversation.

346
00:43:47.877 --> 00:43:49.754
- I have questions.
- They come later.

347
00:43:49.921 --> 00:43:52.298
Who was the warrior in the red armor?

348
00:43:53.299 --> 00:43:56.928
- My brother-in-law. Hirotaro.
- And the woman who cares for me?

349
00:43:57.261 --> 00:43:59.972
My sister. Hirotaro's wife.

350
00:44:00.139 --> 00:44:01.724
Her name is Taka.

351
00:44:02.058 --> 00:44:03.267
I killed her husband?

352
00:44:05.228 --> 00:44:07.438
It was a good death.

353
00:44:20.409 --> 00:44:21.702
You!

354
00:44:55.528 --> 00:44:56.779
Thank you.

355
00:46:19.403 --> 00:46:21.197
Nicely done.

356
00:46:26.827 --> 00:46:27.954
You try.

357
00:46:28.955 --> 00:46:30.373
Try.

358
00:49:39.645 --> 00:49:43.858
I just realized. I've been remiss.
Forgive me.

359
00:49:44.233 --> 00:49:47.653
I have yet to thank you
for looking out for me yesterday.

360
00:49:47.987 --> 00:49:50.198
That is your job. correct?

361
00:49:50.656 --> 00:49:52.325
Protecting me?

362
00:49:53.451 --> 00:49:55.328
Well done. Bob.

363
00:49:55.828 --> 00:49:58.164
You don't mind if I call you "Bob." do you?

364
00:49:58.789 --> 00:50:02.752
I knew a Bob once.
God. he was ugly as a mule.

365
00:50:03.753 --> 00:50:05.713
You a ladies' man. Bob?

366
00:50:09.675 --> 00:50:13.471
Ujio is teaching you the way
of the Japanese sword.

367
00:50:15.181 --> 00:50:16.933
Yes. indeed.

368
00:50:18.809 --> 00:50:22.522
You fought against your Red Indians?

369
00:50:27.235 --> 00:50:28.486
Yes.

370
00:50:28.653 --> 00:50:30.404
Tell me of your part in this war.

371
00:50:30.571 --> 00:50:32.114
- Why?
- I wish to learn.

372
00:50:32.323 --> 00:50:35.660
- Read a book.
- I would rather have a good conversation.

373
00:50:35.826 --> 00:50:37.870
- Why?
- Because...

374
00:50:38.037 --> 00:50:39.914
...we are both students of war.

375
00:50:47.421 --> 00:50:48.798
So...

376
00:50:50.049 --> 00:50:52.593
...you were the general of your army?

377
00:50:55.012 --> 00:50:56.472
No.

378
00:50:57.682 --> 00:51:00.101
I was a captain.

379
00:51:00.518 --> 00:51:02.520
This is a low rank?

380
00:51:04.897 --> 00:51:06.732
A middle rank.

381
00:51:07.984 --> 00:51:09.318
And who was your general?

382
00:51:14.448 --> 00:51:16.868
Don't you have a rebellion to lead?

383
00:51:17.034 --> 00:51:20.371
People in your country
do not like conversation?

384
00:51:20.538 --> 00:51:22.957
He was a lieutenant colonel.

385
00:51:23.624 --> 00:51:25.334
His name was Custer.

386
00:51:25.501 --> 00:51:26.794
I know this name.

387
00:51:27.336 --> 00:51:29.213
He killed many warriors.

388
00:51:29.422 --> 00:51:31.048
Oh. yes. Many warriors.

389
00:51:31.257 --> 00:51:33.384
So he was a good general.

390
00:51:33.593 --> 00:51:37.138
No. No. he wasn't a good general.
He was arrogant and foolhardy.

391
00:51:37.388 --> 00:51:41.684
He got massacred because he took a single
battalion against 2000 angry Indians.

392
00:51:42.185 --> 00:51:44.604
Two thousand Indians?

393
00:51:45.021 --> 00:51:46.314
How many men for Custer?

394
00:51:46.731 --> 00:51:48.149
Two hundred and eleven.

395
00:51:49.609 --> 00:51:51.569
I like this General Custer.

396
00:51:52.111 --> 00:51:56.157
He was a murderer who fell in love
with his own legend.

397
00:51:56.324 --> 00:51:58.451
And his troopers died for it.

398
00:51:58.618 --> 00:52:00.703
I think this is a very good death.

399
00:52:00.870 --> 00:52:02.872
Maybe you can have one
like it someday.

400
00:52:03.080 --> 00:52:05.208
If it is in my destiny.

401
00:52:06.125 --> 00:52:09.170
- What do you want from me?
- What do you want for yourself?

402
00:52:11.797 --> 00:52:13.216
What are you doing?

403
00:52:13.382 --> 00:52:15.510
Why are we having these conversations?

404
00:52:16.260 --> 00:52:18.596
What the hell am I doing here?

405
00:52:23.809 --> 00:52:25.394
In spring...

406
00:52:25.561 --> 00:52:28.940
...the snows will melt
and the passes will open.

407
00:52:30.816 --> 00:52:33.444
Until that time. you are here.

408
00:52:35.321 --> 00:52:38.074
Good day. captain.

409
00:52:59.095 --> 00:53:00.930
<i>1876.</i>

410
00:53:01.097 --> 00:53:04.308
<i>Day unknown. Month unknown.</i>

411
00:53:05.351 --> 00:53:08.980
<i>I continue to live among
these unusual people.</i>

412
00:53:10.273 --> 00:53:13.484
<i>I am their captive.
in that I cannot escape.</i>

413
00:53:15.444 --> 00:53:18.155
<i>Mostly. I'm treated with
a kind of a mild neglect...</i>

414
00:53:19.073 --> 00:53:23.619
<i>...as if I were a stray dog
or an unwelcome guest.</i>

415
00:53:35.298 --> 00:53:38.467
<i>Everyone is polite.
Everyone smiles and bows.</i>

416
00:53:40.219 --> 00:53:44.849
<i>But beneath their courtesy.
I detect a deep reservoir of feeling.</i>

417
00:54:25.389 --> 00:54:27.141
<i>They are an intriguing people.</i>

418
00:54:27.475 --> 00:54:29.227
<i>From the moment they wake...</i>

419
00:54:29.435 --> 00:54:33.439
<i>...they devote themselves to
the perfection of whatever they pursue.</i>

420
00:54:41.989 --> 00:54:44.951
<i>I have never seen such discipline.</i>

421
00:54:46.035 --> 00:54:50.164
<i>I am surprised to learn that the word
"Samurai" means "to serve"...</i>

422
00:54:50.331 --> 00:54:54.877
<i>...and that Katsumoto believes his rebellion
to be in the service of the Emperor.</i>

423
00:56:56.749 --> 00:56:59.377
Please forgive. Too many mind.

424
00:57:00.837 --> 00:57:02.630
Too many mind?

425
00:57:03.172 --> 00:57:07.468
Mind sword. mind people watch.
mind enemy.

426
00:57:08.302 --> 00:57:10.096
Too many mind.

427
00:57:12.098 --> 00:57:13.349
No mind.

428
00:57:15.351 --> 00:57:16.894
No mind.

429
00:57:58.644 --> 00:58:01.022
Not so fast. What are these?

430
00:58:16.954 --> 00:58:18.372
No. no. Not so fast.

431
00:58:22.585 --> 00:58:23.794
I'm Algren.

432
00:58:31.594 --> 00:58:34.430
- Nobutada.
- Nobutada.

433
00:58:35.139 --> 00:58:37.058
- Magojiro.
- Magojiro.

434
00:58:37.225 --> 00:58:38.476
Higen.

435
00:58:39.143 --> 00:58:40.520
Higen.

436
00:58:44.106 --> 00:58:45.441
Taka.

437
00:59:54.594 --> 00:59:56.637
She's been very kind to me.

438
00:59:57.597 --> 01:00:01.559
She's honored to have
my guest in her house.

439
01:00:26.042 --> 01:00:28.753
<i>Winter. 1877.</i>

440
01:00:29.003 --> 01:00:31.631
<i>What does it mean to be Samurai?</i>

441
01:00:31.797 --> 01:00:35.218
<i>To devote yourself utterly
to a set of moral principles...</i>

442
01:00:35.927 --> 01:00:38.846
<i>...to seek a stillness of your mind...</i>

443
01:00:39.472 --> 01:00:42.725
<i>...and to master the way of the sword.</i>

444
01:00:57.240 --> 01:00:58.616
Cold?

445
01:01:10.419 --> 01:01:11.796
Also. Also cold.

446
01:01:12.839 --> 01:01:14.173
Fire.

447
01:01:22.765 --> 01:01:24.350
To burn.

448
01:02:23.284 --> 01:02:24.535
I'm sorry.

449
01:02:34.086 --> 01:02:37.006
For your husband. Hirotaro.

450
01:03:29.308 --> 01:03:32.103
<i>Spring. 1877.</i>

451
01:03:32.562 --> 01:03:37.525
<i>This marks the longest I have stayed
in one place since I left the farm at 17.</i>

452
01:03:41.028 --> 01:03:44.365
<i>There is so much here
that I'll never understand.</i>

453
01:03:48.744 --> 01:03:51.539
<i>I have never been a church-going man...</i>

454
01:03:51.706 --> 01:03:56.127
<i>...and what I've seen on the field of battle
has led me to question God's purpose.</i>

455
01:03:56.294 --> 01:03:58.629
<i>But there is. indeed. something...</i>

456
01:03:58.838 --> 01:04:01.883
<i>...spiritual in this place.</i>

457
01:04:05.178 --> 01:04:08.639
<i>And though it may forever
be obscure to me...</i>

458
01:04:08.806 --> 01:04:12.268
<i>...I cannot but be aware of its power.</i>

459
01:04:20.735 --> 01:04:25.656
<i>I do know it is here that I have known
my first untroubled sleep in many years.</i>

460
01:04:29.035 --> 01:04:31.996
No. you gotta get the ball!
Go and get it.

461
01:04:32.163 --> 01:04:36.292
No. not me!
You gotta get the ball! The ball!

462
01:05:29.637 --> 01:05:31.305
No mind.

463
01:08:26.856 --> 01:08:28.232
Katsumoto!

464
01:11:55.273 --> 01:11:58.609
The perfect blossom is a rare thing.

465
01:11:58.776 --> 01:12:03.781
You could spend your life looking for one.
and it would not be a wasted life.

466
01:12:04.615 --> 01:12:06.576
Who sent those men to kill you?

467
01:12:06.784 --> 01:12:09.871
I'm writing a poem about a dream I had.

468
01:12:10.371 --> 01:12:13.249
<i>The tiger's eyes are like my own</i>

469
01:12:13.416 --> 01:12:16.627
<i>But he comes from across
A deep and troubled sea</i>

470
01:12:17.545 --> 01:12:19.380
Was it the Emperor?

471
01:12:21.215 --> 01:12:22.508
Omura?

472
01:12:22.675 --> 01:12:26.596
If the Emperor wishes my death.
he has but to ask.

473
01:12:27.513 --> 01:12:29.348
So it was Omura.

474
01:12:29.932 --> 01:12:32.101
I'm having trouble finishing the poem.

475
01:12:32.268 --> 01:12:35.938
- Can you suggest a last line?
- I'm not a writer.

476
01:12:36.189 --> 01:12:41.194
Yet you have written many pages
since you came here.

477
01:12:43.654 --> 01:12:45.781
What else has she told you?

478
01:12:47.658 --> 01:12:49.744
You have nightmares.

479
01:12:52.580 --> 01:12:54.123
Every soldier has nightmares.

480
01:12:54.290 --> 01:12:57.752
Only one who is ashamed
of what he has done.

481
01:12:58.503 --> 01:13:01.714
You have no idea what I have done.

482
01:13:08.971 --> 01:13:12.141
You have seen many things.

483
01:13:13.184 --> 01:13:14.185
I have.

484
01:13:14.352 --> 01:13:18.606
And you do not fear death.
but sometimes you wish for it.

485
01:13:19.148 --> 01:13:21.150
Is this not so?

486
01:13:23.736 --> 01:13:26.322
- Yes.
- I. also.

487
01:13:27.198 --> 01:13:31.285
It happens to men who have seen
what we have seen.

488
01:13:31.827 --> 01:13:37.291
And then I come to this place
of my ancestors...

489
01:13:37.583 --> 01:13:39.585
...and I remember.

490
01:13:39.752 --> 01:13:42.046
Like these blossoms...

491
01:13:42.797 --> 01:13:44.841
...we are all dying.

492
01:13:46.717 --> 01:13:50.179
To know life in every breath...

493
01:13:50.888 --> 01:13:53.140
...every cup of tea...

494
01:13:53.307 --> 01:13:56.352
...every life we take.

495
01:13:56.519 --> 01:13:58.896
The way of the warrior.

496
01:13:59.063 --> 01:14:01.232
Life in every breath.

497
01:14:02.358 --> 01:14:04.569
That is Bushido.

498
01:14:08.906 --> 01:14:12.535
The Emperor has granted
a safe passage to Tokyo.

499
01:14:13.202 --> 01:14:15.204
We leave tomorrow.

500
01:14:18.082 --> 01:14:19.542
Good.

501
01:14:20.626 --> 01:14:21.961
Good.

502
01:14:28.551 --> 01:14:31.512
When I took these. you were...

503
01:14:32.388 --> 01:14:33.973
...my enemy.

504
01:16:17.451 --> 01:16:21.122
Algren-san! Algren-san.

505
01:19:15.379 --> 01:19:17.048
Algren?

506
01:19:17.215 --> 01:19:20.134
Algren. my God. you are alive.

507
01:19:24.222 --> 01:19:26.682
Well. you never cease to astonish.

508
01:19:27.391 --> 01:19:31.145
- Howitzers.
- Yes. indeed.

509
01:19:31.312 --> 01:19:34.065
As soon as the Emperor signs
the trade agreement...

510
01:19:34.232 --> 01:19:36.359
...he gets the whole package.

511
01:19:36.526 --> 01:19:40.029
Including this particular item.
Two hundred rounds a minute.

512
01:19:40.488 --> 01:19:43.699
And the new cartridges
cut down on jamming.

513
01:19:43.866 --> 01:19:45.576
I need a bath.

514
01:19:45.743 --> 01:19:49.372
After living with those savages.
I can only imagine.

515
01:19:50.915 --> 01:19:53.125
Welcome back. captain.

516
01:21:24.008 --> 01:21:26.594
Gentlemen. come in.

517
01:21:27.094 --> 01:21:31.766
Captain Algren. it seems you have
endured your captivity with little ill effect.

518
01:21:32.683 --> 01:21:34.268
I was not ill-treated. sir.

519
01:21:34.435 --> 01:21:38.022
Mr. Omura. I have here
a draft of the arms agreement.

520
01:21:38.189 --> 01:21:41.984
I'm eager to know how many Samurai
have joined Katsumoto.

521
01:21:42.193 --> 01:21:43.611
I'm afraid I don't know.

522
01:21:43.778 --> 01:21:47.156
- You spent the winter at his encampment.
- As his prisoner.

523
01:21:47.323 --> 01:21:51.536
Has he fortified his position?
Acquired firearms? Tell us what you saw.

524
01:21:51.702 --> 01:21:57.041
As you said. colonel.
they're savages with bows and arrows.

525
01:21:57.208 --> 01:22:01.170
- Sir. about the...
- I'm sure your documents are in order.

526
01:22:01.379 --> 01:22:05.800
Thank you. Leave them on my desk.
I'll address them at the appropriate time.

527
01:22:05.967 --> 01:22:10.346
With all due respect. sir.
our president's patience is wearing thin.

528
01:22:10.513 --> 01:22:13.015
Perhaps there is someone else
we should speak to.

529
01:22:13.224 --> 01:22:15.560
With all due respect. ambassador...

530
01:22:15.726 --> 01:22:18.479
...perhaps there is someone else
we should speak to.

531
01:22:18.646 --> 01:22:21.399
For instance. the French
or the English.

532
01:22:21.566 --> 01:22:24.694
Or any of the legations
waiting in the next room.

533
01:22:26.445 --> 01:22:29.699
We should be looking forward
to hearing from you.

534
01:22:30.491 --> 01:22:34.120
Good afternoon. gentlemen.
Captain Algren.

535
01:22:34.620 --> 01:22:39.375
Perhaps you and I might have
a word in private. Please. sit down.

536
01:22:42.461 --> 01:22:45.756
- May I offer you whiskey?
- No. thank you.

537
01:22:52.096 --> 01:22:55.224
Katsumoto is an extraordinary man.
is he not?

538
01:22:55.433 --> 01:22:59.103
He's a tribal leader.
I've known many of them.

539
01:22:59.270 --> 01:23:04.233
But none who are Samurai.
Their ways have great appeal.

540
01:23:04.442 --> 01:23:08.321
- I don't see how this concerns me.
- But it does.

541
01:23:08.487 --> 01:23:13.743
You see. you were right. Last year.
we were not prepared to go to battle.

542
01:23:13.910 --> 01:23:16.537
You were right.
and Colonel Bagley was wrong.

543
01:23:16.704 --> 01:23:18.623
But now. we are ready.

544
01:23:18.789 --> 01:23:22.251
If Katsumoto is allowed to attract
other Samurai to his cause...

545
01:23:22.418 --> 01:23:27.256
...we will have 10 years of rebellion.
This is something I will not allow.

546
01:23:27.423 --> 01:23:32.970
Either I'll stop him at the council today.
or you'll lead my army against him.

547
01:23:33.137 --> 01:23:37.266
And with these new weapons.
you will crush him.

548
01:23:39.101 --> 01:23:42.605
- I appreciate the offer.
- It is not an offer.

549
01:23:43.397 --> 01:23:47.443
Mr. Omura. my contract with you
was to train your army.

550
01:23:47.652 --> 01:23:50.112
Then we will make a new contract...

551
01:23:50.321 --> 01:23:55.493
...one that will recognize the extraordinary
contribution you've made to the Emperor.

552
01:23:55.993 --> 01:23:58.287
Do we understand each other?

553
01:24:00.873 --> 01:24:04.836
- Yes. we understand each other perfectly.
- Then I am pleased.

554
01:24:22.979 --> 01:24:25.815
Captain Algren!
What in heaven's name is going on?

555
01:24:25.982 --> 01:24:27.984
The diplomatic community is abuzz.

556
01:24:28.150 --> 01:24:30.862
Omura has passed laws
against the Samurai.

557
01:24:31.028 --> 01:24:32.238
I need a drink.

558
01:24:32.405 --> 01:24:37.493
Is your friend Katsumoto really planning
to go up against the council this afternoon?

559
01:24:44.041 --> 01:24:45.168
My God. it's started.

560
01:24:56.137 --> 01:24:57.180
Captain Algren!

561
01:26:11.170 --> 01:26:12.839
Jolly good.

562
01:29:04.343 --> 01:29:06.345
I heard you were leaving.

563
01:29:08.139 --> 01:29:11.184
Omura offers you my job.
and you run away.

564
01:29:12.268 --> 01:29:14.437
I suppose I should thank you.

565
01:29:15.021 --> 01:29:19.567
$500 a month. including
back pay for time spent...

566
01:29:19.984 --> 01:29:21.819
...in captivity.

567
01:29:23.404 --> 01:29:26.741
Enough to climb back inside a bottle
for the rest of your life.

568
01:29:30.161 --> 01:29:31.621
You're welcome.

569
01:29:36.792 --> 01:29:39.337
Well. it is pretty much over.

570
01:29:39.504 --> 01:29:43.883
Katsumoto's under arrest.
Omura won't let him last the night.

571
01:29:44.050 --> 01:29:48.429
With him dead. we should have
little trouble handling the rebellion...

572
01:29:48.596 --> 01:29:50.306
...even without you.

573
01:29:54.685 --> 01:29:57.021
Especially without you.

574
01:30:01.984 --> 01:30:04.195
Just tell me one thing.

575
01:30:04.820 --> 01:30:09.075
What is it about your own people
that you hate so much?

576
01:34:24.830 --> 01:34:27.500
Don't stop.
Whatever you do. don't stop.

577
01:35:13.045 --> 01:35:16.132
- President of the United States?
- Sorry.

578
01:35:16.299 --> 01:35:18.092
I think I'm going to be sick.

579
01:35:36.360 --> 01:35:38.404
How's your poem coming?

580
01:35:41.032 --> 01:35:43.910
The end is proving difficult.

581
01:35:44.076 --> 01:35:48.039
This is Mr. Simon Graham. He'd like
very much to take your photograph.

582
01:35:49.498 --> 01:35:51.667
I thought you returned to America.

583
01:35:51.834 --> 01:35:56.547
I decided to stay.
See if I could convince you to escape.

584
01:35:56.797 --> 01:35:58.925
How do you plan to do that?

585
01:36:07.725 --> 01:36:11.729
Mr. Graham. perhaps you would care
to take pictures of my village.

586
01:36:11.896 --> 01:36:14.106
I would be greatly honored.

587
01:40:12.595 --> 01:40:15.515
The Emperor could not hear my words.

588
01:40:17.850 --> 01:40:20.353
His army will come.

589
01:40:21.604 --> 01:40:23.564
It is the end.

590
01:40:26.025 --> 01:40:30.571
For 900 years. my ancestors
have protected our people.

591
01:40:32.240 --> 01:40:34.492
Now...

592
01:40:34.659 --> 01:40:36.369
...I have failed them.

593
01:40:47.922 --> 01:40:51.300
So you will take your own life...

594
01:40:52.885 --> 01:40:54.136
...in shame?

595
01:40:59.350 --> 01:41:02.979
Shame for a life of service?

596
01:41:03.980 --> 01:41:06.774
Discipline? Compassion?

597
01:41:07.608 --> 01:41:11.070
The way of the Samurai
is not necessary anymore.

598
01:41:11.237 --> 01:41:13.656
Necessary?

599
01:41:15.658 --> 01:41:18.160
What could be more necessary?

600
01:41:22.248 --> 01:41:25.793
I will die by the sword.

601
01:41:27.545 --> 01:41:29.964
My own...

602
01:41:30.131 --> 01:41:31.966
...or my enemy's.

603
01:41:33.134 --> 01:41:35.261
Then let it be your enemy's.

604
01:41:38.848 --> 01:41:42.643
Together. we will make
the Emperor hear you.

605
01:44:23.888 --> 01:44:25.765
Algren.

606
01:44:56.546 --> 01:44:58.631
I'd say two full regiments.

607
01:44:58.798 --> 01:45:01.050
They'll come in waves of a thousand.

608
01:45:01.634 --> 01:45:03.261
And they have the howitzers.

609
01:45:03.427 --> 01:45:07.682
It makes no difference. They will come.
and we will make our stand.

610
01:45:07.849 --> 01:45:10.852
- How many men will we have?
- Maybe 500.

611
01:45:11.477 --> 01:45:13.229
Like General Custer. huh?

612
01:45:17.567 --> 01:45:21.612
There was once a battle
at a place called Thermopylae.

613
01:45:21.779 --> 01:45:25.366
Three hundred brave Greeks held off
a Persian army of a million men.

614
01:45:25.533 --> 01:45:28.119
A million. You understand this number?

615
01:45:28.286 --> 01:45:30.288
I understand this number.

616
01:45:30.538 --> 01:45:33.124
For two days the Greeks
made them pay so dearly...

617
01:45:33.291 --> 01:45:38.629
...the Persian army lost all taste
for battle and were defeated soon after.

618
01:45:38.796 --> 01:45:42.925
- What do you have in mind?
- Take away the advantage of their guns.

619
01:45:43.176 --> 01:45:46.679
They're overconfident. We'll use that.
Lure them close.

620
01:45:47.847 --> 01:45:49.390
Close enough for a sword.

621
01:45:51.142 --> 01:45:53.394
You believe...

622
01:45:53.603 --> 01:45:55.688
...a man can change his destiny?

623
01:45:58.608 --> 01:46:01.777
I think a man does what he can...

624
01:46:01.944 --> 01:46:04.071
...until his destiny is revealed to him.

625
01:46:11.495 --> 01:46:15.166
<i>May 25th. 1877.</i>

626
01:46:15.333 --> 01:46:18.461
<i>This will be the last entry
in this journal.</i>

627
01:46:18.628 --> 01:46:23.883
<i>I've tried to give a true accounting
of what I have seen. what I have done.</i>

628
01:46:24.050 --> 01:46:27.595
<i>I do not presume to understand
the course of my life.</i>

629
01:46:27.970 --> 01:46:32.016
<i>I know I am grateful
to have partaken of all this...</i>

630
01:46:32.183 --> 01:46:34.227
<i>...even if for a moment.</i>

631
01:51:50.084 --> 01:51:52.920
You will need this.

632
01:52:04.807 --> 01:52:06.100
What does it say?

633
01:52:07.185 --> 01:52:12.648
"I belong to the warrior in whom
the old ways have joined the new. "

634
01:53:16.712 --> 01:53:19.173
Good God.

635
01:53:22.718 --> 01:53:26.806
Sir. the Imperial Army of Japan
demands your surrender.

636
01:53:27.223 --> 01:53:29.851
If you lay down your arms.
you will not be harmed.

637
01:53:30.184 --> 01:53:34.689
This is not possible.
as Mr. Omura knows.

638
01:53:38.901 --> 01:53:40.820
Captain Algren.

639
01:53:40.987 --> 01:53:42.864
We will show you no quarter.

640
01:53:43.072 --> 01:53:45.700
You ride against us.
and you are the same as them.

641
01:53:46.742 --> 01:53:48.744
I'll look for you on the field.

642
01:54:09.557 --> 01:54:11.017
Captain Algren.

643
01:54:11.184 --> 01:54:13.769
Mr. Graham.

644
01:54:17.106 --> 01:54:20.443
Perhaps you can use these
for your book.

645
01:54:20.610 --> 01:54:23.070
Yes. I will. Captain.

646
01:54:26.240 --> 01:54:27.950
Godspeed.

647
01:54:29.619 --> 01:54:31.954
Mr. Graham.

648
01:55:54.871 --> 01:55:57.665
Commence firing!

649
01:57:13.533 --> 01:57:16.077
- They're covering their retreat.
- You see?

650
01:57:16.285 --> 01:57:20.039
Even the mighty Samurai
cannot stand up to the howitzers.

651
01:57:20.206 --> 01:57:23.417
- Signal the attack.
- I advise sending in skirmishers first.

652
01:57:23.584 --> 01:57:25.545
Nonsense! Full attack!

653
01:58:21.309 --> 01:58:23.519
They're coming.

654
01:58:55.885 --> 01:58:57.803
Wait for the volley.

655
01:59:09.565 --> 01:59:11.400
Second volley.

656
02:00:06.205 --> 02:00:08.457
- What on earth?
- What is happening?

657
02:00:53.294 --> 02:00:56.631
- The attack has been stopped.
- Send in the rest of the regiment.

658
02:01:01.594 --> 02:01:03.846
What happened to the warriors
at Thermopylae?

659
02:01:04.263 --> 02:01:07.016
Dead to the last man.

660
02:02:10.079 --> 02:02:11.873
Algren-san!

661
02:05:00.374 --> 02:05:03.211
Son of a bitch thinks he can win.

662
02:06:07.441 --> 02:06:11.320
They'll bring two more regiments
up here soon.

663
02:06:11.487 --> 02:06:13.573
We won't be able to stop them again.

664
02:06:14.574 --> 02:06:16.617
You do not have to die here.

665
02:06:19.662 --> 02:06:22.456
I should have died
so many times before.

666
02:06:22.999 --> 02:06:24.417
Now. you live again.

667
02:06:27.628 --> 02:06:29.839
Yes.

668
02:06:32.008 --> 02:06:34.969
It was not your time.

669
02:06:38.347 --> 02:06:40.641
It's not over.

670
02:07:26.979 --> 02:07:28.356
What is this?

671
02:07:32.652 --> 02:07:36.989
- This is madness. He's going to attack?
- Yes.

672
02:07:45.248 --> 02:07:48.334
He's defeated!
He must accept his shame!

673
02:08:00.304 --> 02:08:02.723
Kill him. All of them.

674
02:08:02.890 --> 02:08:05.268
Now!

675
02:08:09.355 --> 02:08:10.690
My horse!

676
02:09:03.618 --> 02:09:04.869
Fire!

677
02:09:41.906 --> 02:09:43.241
Ready!

678
02:09:46.619 --> 02:09:47.870
Aim!

679
02:09:53.209 --> 02:09:54.585
Fire!

680
02:10:00.716 --> 02:10:02.218
Fire at will!

681
02:11:01.319 --> 02:11:02.612
Backward!

682
02:13:12.617 --> 02:13:14.035
No.

683
02:13:21.167 --> 02:13:23.878
You have your honor again.

684
02:13:26.088 --> 02:13:28.382
Let me die with mine.

685
02:13:37.767 --> 02:13:39.810
Help me up.

686
02:13:59.413 --> 02:14:01.082
Are you ready?

687
02:14:08.256 --> 02:14:11.926
I will miss our conversations.

688
02:14:58.472 --> 02:15:00.808
Perfect.

689
02:15:07.398 --> 02:15:10.610
They are all...

690
02:15:11.611 --> 02:15:13.738
...perfect.

691
02:16:41.826 --> 02:16:45.454
<i>On behalf of the United States of America...</i>

692
02:16:46.414 --> 02:16:51.627
...the signing of this treaty will usher in
an era of unprecedented prosperity...

693
02:16:51.794 --> 02:16:55.923
...and cooperation between
our two great nations.

694
02:16:56.257 --> 02:16:58.009
On behalf of the Emperor...

695
02:16:58.176 --> 02:17:01.929
...we are pleased to have
successfully concluded this...

696
02:17:05.308 --> 02:17:07.602
...negotiation.

697
02:18:51.831 --> 02:18:54.667
This is Katsumoto's sword.

698
02:18:56.002 --> 02:18:58.713
He would have wanted you to have it...

699
02:18:59.881 --> 02:19:02.925
...that the strength of the Samurai
be with you always.

700
02:19:09.015 --> 02:19:10.558
He hoped...

701
02:19:11.225 --> 02:19:13.394
...with his last breath...

702
02:19:13.811 --> 02:19:17.190
...that you would remember the ancestors
who held this sword...

703
02:19:18.941 --> 02:19:21.235
...and what they died for.

704
02:19:41.464 --> 02:19:43.716
You were with him...

705
02:19:44.884 --> 02:19:46.928
...at the end?

706
02:19:52.308 --> 02:19:55.770
Emperor. this man fought against you!

707
02:19:59.982 --> 02:20:01.609
Your Highness...

708
02:20:02.902 --> 02:20:07.448
...if you believe me to be your enemy.
command me...

709
02:20:07.615 --> 02:20:09.951
...and I will gladly take my life.

710
02:20:24.090 --> 02:20:28.135
I have dreamed of a unified Japan...

711
02:20:28.302 --> 02:20:34.141
...of a country strong
and independent and modern.

712
02:20:34.308 --> 02:20:40.106
And now we have railroads
and cannon. Western clothing.

713
02:20:42.024 --> 02:20:43.651
But...

714
02:20:47.029 --> 02:20:51.117
...we cannot forget who we are...

715
02:20:52.535 --> 02:20:57.039
...or where we come from.

716
02:21:09.468 --> 02:21:12.013
Ambassador Swanbeck...

717
02:21:12.180 --> 02:21:15.016
...I have concluded that your treaty...

718
02:21:15.183 --> 02:21:20.021
...is not in the best interest of my people.

719
02:21:20.813 --> 02:21:24.442
- Sir. if I may...
- So sorry...

720
02:21:24.817 --> 02:21:26.569
...but you may not.

721
02:21:26.903 --> 02:21:30.239
This is an outrage!

722
02:22:36.848 --> 02:22:39.392
Tell me how he died.

723
02:22:47.108 --> 02:22:51.696
I will tell you how he lived.

724
02:23:00.955 --> 02:23:05.376
<i>And so the days
of the Samurai had ended.</i>

725
02:23:05.543 --> 02:23:11.090
<i>Nations. like men. it is sometimes said.
have their own destiny.</i>

726
02:23:12.133 --> 02:23:14.760
<i>As for the American captain...</i>

727
02:23:14.927 --> 02:23:17.263
<i>...no one knows what became of him.</i>

728
02:23:17.430 --> 02:23:20.850
<i>Some say that he died of his wounds...</i>

729
02:23:21.017 --> 02:23:24.979
<i>...others. that he returned
to his own country.</i>

730
02:23:25.146 --> 02:23:26.772
<i>But I like to think...</i>

731
02:23:26.981 --> 02:23:32.028
<i>...he may have at last found
some small measure of peace...</i>

732
02:23:32.195 --> 02:23:34.197
<i>...that we all seek...</i>

733
02:23:34.989 --> 02:23:38.159
<i>...and few of us ever find.</i>

734
02:23:39.305 --> 02:24:39.201
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
